At the end of 2014, I used $700 to start my business. I bought a membership at a maker space and took classes on operating a laser. I paid by the hour to run my files on their laser before I could afford my own. I ordered wood and acrylic and made a few mock up cake toppers. I ordered shipping supplies, business cards, and even bought plaster and foam to make a fake wedding cake. 🎂😂 I took photos of the cake toppers on my phone in my tiny apartment and listed them on Etsy and hoped for the best. 

This month, I am celebrating SIX YEARS full time with my business (I left my corporate design job in February 2017!) and I seriously cannot believe it. It’s grown SLOWLY but SUSTAINABLY and I am so proud of that. 

Don’t let the “don’t haves” stop you from going after your dreams. Start small. Start with where you are, with what you have, and keep going. I’ve added tools equipment, staff, and “things” as our sales have grown. It’s totally possible to start small and grow from there! 💪❤️
___
#smallbusiness #youcandohardthings #smallbusinessbigdreams #handsandhustle #workhardstayhumble

It’s been WAAAAYYYY too long since I’ve done a #selfiewithyoursign (IYKYK).

A few years ago, I used to selfie with projects all the time. I honestly didn’t think too much on what I shared, but I showed up consistently. It can be really easy to let the “should do’s” and “algorithm rules” keep you from doing anything on this platform. I’m so guilty of it in the last year… it almost is paralyzing. 

But I just decided that waiting to share cool work until I am a TikTok influencer or a master of reels is silly. 🙃 If you’re a content creator of any sort, allow this to be the permission you need to just 👏 hit 👏 post. 👏 

Something is better than nothing. ❤️
